%N A279280 Expansion of Product_{k>=1} (1 + x^(k*(5*k-3)/2)).
%C A279280 Number of partitions of n into distinct heptagonal numbers (A000566).
%H A279280 Vaclav Kotesovec, <a href="/A279280/b279280.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..20000</a>
%H A279280 Vaclav Kotesovec, <a href="/A279280/a279280.jpg">Graph - the asymptotic ratio (100000 terms)</a>
%H A279280 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/HeptagonalNumber.html">Heptagonal Number</a>
%H A279280 <a href="/index/Pol#polygonal_numbers">Index to sequences related to polygonal numbers</a>
%H A279280 <a href="/index/Par#partN">Index entries for related partition-counting sequences</a>
%F A279280 G.f.: Product_{k>=1} (1 + x^(k*(5*k-3)/2)).
%F A279280 a(n) ~ zeta(3/2)^(1/3) * (sqrt(2) - 1)^(1/3) * exp(3*Pi^(1/3) * zeta(3/2)^(2/3) * (sqrt(2) - 1)^(2/3) * n^(1/3) / (2^(5/3)*d^(1/3))) / (2^(4/3 + b/(2*d)) * sqrt(3) * d^(1/6) * Pi^(1/3) * n^(5/6)) * (1 - ((sqrt(2) - 1)^(4/3) * b^2 * Pi^(2/3) * zeta(1/2) * zeta(3/2)^(1/3) / (2^(23/6) * d^(5/3)) + 5*d^(1/3) / (9 * (2*Pi)^(1/3) * (sqrt(2) - 1)^(2/3) * zeta(3/2)^(2/3))) / n^(1/3)), where d = 5/2, b = -3/2. - _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 11 2026
%e A279280 a(81) = 2 because we have [81] and [55, 18, 7, 1].
%t A279280 nmax = 120; CoefficientList[Series[Product[1 + x^(k*(5*k-3)/2), {k, 1, Sqrt[9 + 40 nmax]/10 + 1}], {x, 0, nmax}], x] (* tuned for efficiency by _Vaclav Kotesovec_, Mar 10 2026 *)
